---
import BaseCaseStudy from '../layouts/BaseCaseStudy.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const pains = [
  { t: 'Weak working memory', d: 'Plans and detailed steps vanish the moment you stop actively holding them.' },
  { t: 'Gendered presentation', d: 'Symptoms read as inattentive rather than hyperactive, so they go unnamed.' },
  { t: 'Misinterpretation', d: 'Executive-function failures mistaken for laziness, eroding self-confidence.' },
  { t: 'Time blindness', d: 'Inability to accurately sense how long tasks will take.' },
  { t: 'Daily forgetfulness', d: 'Chronic struggles with remembering tasks, items, and appointments.' },
  { t: 'Planning burnout', d: 'Exhaustion from the mental effort of organising thought itself.' },
];

const voices = [
  '"I\'m quiet and seem calm, but my mind is always running — like too many browser tabs open at once."',
  '"I thought I was lazy and undisciplined. After years of mistakes and being fired, I finally realised my attention was never really online."',
  '"This fits me perfectly, but I\'m still scared I\'m just overthinking it and don\'t actually have ADHD."',
  '"I can see what I need to do, but I can\'t find the key to start. The anxiety builds, but my body won\'t move."',
];

const values = [
  {
    t: 'Cognitive accessibility',
    d: 'Bright colours, high contrast, and clear colour coding to reduce cognitive load. For ADHD or dyslexia traits, immediate visual cues outperform minimalist interfaces — which meant resisting the urge to make it look like a generic Scandinavian wellness app.',
  },
  {
    t: 'Positive reinforcement',
    d: 'No streaks that punish you for missing a day. Gamified elements as gentle motivation, not surveillance. The design prioritises encouragement over productivity guilt.',
  },
  {
    t: 'Readability',
    d: 'Larger, rounded typography to reduce visual strain during attention fatigue, supporting users with reading difficulty or cognitive overload.',
  },
];
---

<BaseCaseStudy title="Fidgi Grow — Jielle Lu">
  <main class="relative z-10 mx-auto max-w-[1200px] min-h-screen px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 pt-8 md:pt-10 pb-24">

    <!-- TOP CHROME -->
    <header class="flex items-start justify-between gap-6 font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em]">
      <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-white/70 hover:text-white transition-colors">
        <span>←</span> Home
      </a>
      <div class="text-right space-y-0.5 text-white/55">
        <div class="text-white/80">§ 02 — Case study</div>
        <div>Vol. I · 2025 · Interdisciplinary studio</div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- HERO -->
    <section class="mt-16 md:mt-24 grid grid-cols-12 gap-6 md:gap-10">
      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8">
        <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/55 mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
          <span class="text-white text-base leading-none">◆</span>
          <span>Chapter Two — Fidgi Grow</span>
        </div>

        <h1 class="font-sans font-black tracking-[-0.055em] leading-[0.88] text-white text-[clamp(64px,11vw,176px)]">
          <span class="block">Fidgi</span>
          <span
            class="block font-light italic text-white/60 tracking-[-0.025em]"
            style="font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-variation-settings: 'SOFT' 100, 'WONK' 1, 'opsz' 144;"
          >
            Grow.
          </span>
        </h1>

        <p class="mt-10 max-w-[52ch] text-[17px] leading-[1.55] text-white/80">
          An ADHD support app that
          <span class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">never mentions ADHD</span>
          on its cover.
        </p>
      </div>

      <aside class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 md:pt-16">
        <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/50 border-b border-white/15 pb-2 mb-5">
          Reader's guide
        </div>
        <ul class="space-y-4 text-[15px] leading-[1.4] text-white/75" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-style:italic">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60">→</span><span>§1 the week research broke our brief.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60">→</span><span>§2 the positioning statement that carried the whole thing.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60">→</span><span>§3 – §4 design decisions and features in full.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60">→</span><span>§5 an iteration, and what it taught us.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <!-- META + MY ROLE -->
    <section class="mt-20 md:mt-28 grid grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
        <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-b border-white/15 pb-3 mb-5">
          <span class="text-white/80">§</span> Project meta
        </div>
        <dl class="space-y-3 text-[14.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/75">
          <div class="flex gap-4"><dt class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/45 w-[88px] shrink-0 pt-[3px]">Year</dt><dd>2025 · Interdisciplinary studio</dd></div>
          <div class="flex gap-4"><dt class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/45 w-[88px] shrink-0 pt-[3px]">Team</dt><dd>5 — UI, research, writing, industrial design</dd></div>
          <div class="flex gap-4"><dt class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/45 w-[88px] shrink-0 pt-[3px]">Role</dt><dd>UI design · Research & strategy</dd></div>
          <div class="flex gap-4"><dt class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/45 w-[88px] shrink-0 pt-[3px]">Tools</dt><dd>Figma</dd></div>
          <div class="flex gap-4"><dt class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/45 w-[88px] shrink-0 pt-[3px]">Tags</dt><dd class="text-white/55">Mobile · Healthcare · ADHD · Inclusive · Hardware × software</dd></div>
        </dl>
      </div>

      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8">
        <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-b border-white/15 pb-3 mb-5">
          <span class="text-white/80">§</span> My role
        </div>
        <p class="text-[15.5px] leading-[1.6] text-white/80 max-w-[62ch]">
          A 5-person team project across UX research, UI design, writing, and industrial design.
          My specific contributions:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-[15px] leading-[1.55] text-white/85">
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">·</span>
            <span><strong class="text-white">Research synthesis</strong> — organised findings into the six pain points that drove the design priorities, and helped shape the "Real Voice of ADHD" evidence that anchored our brief.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">·</span>
            <span><strong class="text-white">UI design</strong> — onboarding flow (gender-inclusive registration), the hormone-aware calendar, and the gamified tracking overview.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">·</span>
            <span><strong class="text-white">Strategy discussions</strong> — participated in shaping the "Optimized for ADHD women, built for everyone" positioning, which defined how the product framed itself.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-5 text-[14px] leading-[1.55] text-white/55 max-w-[62ch]">
          The physical fidget toy was led by our industrial design teammate; I contributed to how the toy's data integrated into the app UI.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE QUESTION -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§</span> The question
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-white leading-[0.95] max-w-[22ch]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-size:clamp(32px,5vw,56px);letter-spacing:-0.03em">
        Most ADHD apps <span class="italic text-white/60">announce it on the cover.</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-8 text-[15.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[62ch]">
        Notion for ADHD. Tiimo for ADHD. Inflow for ADHD.
        We spent the first week of the project assuming we'd do the same —
        <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">and then the research broke that assumption.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- §1 RESEARCH -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 01</span> — What the research showed
      </div>

      <!-- Competitor landscape -->
      <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-8 mb-16">
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[20px] leading-[1.25] text-white">A saturated market with a specific blind spot</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8">
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[60ch] mb-6">
            The productivity market is crowded with task and focus tools, and there's a smaller neurodivergent-specific segment. Both are useful, but share the same gap: they treat ADHD symptoms as static and universal, and rarely account for <strong class="text-white">hormonal fluctuation</strong> or <strong class="text-white">internalized symptom patterns</strong> — exactly the things that make ADHD look different in women.
          </p>
          <div class="rounded-[12px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden text-[13.5px]">
            <table class="w-full">
              <thead class="bg-white/[0.05] font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/55">
                <tr>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-normal">Category</th>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-normal">Strength</th>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-normal">Weakness</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr class="bg-white/[0.015]">
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white font-medium">Robust platforms <span class="text-white/50 font-normal">(Todoist, Notion)</span></td>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white/70">Flexible, powerful, huge user base</td>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white/50">Too overwhelming for exec dysfunction; no ADHD-specific tooling</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white font-medium">Neurodivergent tools <span class="text-white/50 font-normal">(Inflow, Tiimo)</span></td>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white/70">Timers, routines, education</td>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white/50">Expensive; less focus on inattentive presentations</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="bg-white/[0.015]">
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white font-medium">Single-purpose <span class="text-white/50 font-normal">(Forest)</span></td>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white/70">Excellent at one thing</td>
                  <td class="py-3 px-4 text-white/50">Forces users to juggle multiple apps</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Women's ADHD blind spot -->
      <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-8">
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[20px] leading-[1.25] text-white">Women's ADHD is a gendered blind spot</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8">
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[60ch]">
            ADHD in women isn't rarer — it's under-recognised. The childhood diagnosis ratio skews male 2:1,
            but in adulthood the ratio balances out. That gap is a story about what gets seen, not what exists.
            Women's symptoms tend to be internalised rather than hyperactive: distractibility, forgetfulness,
            planning paralysis. These look less like "ADHD" and more like
            <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">"bad at life"</em> — which is exactly how many women come to describe themselves.
          </p>
          <figure class="mt-6 border-l-2 border-white/35 pl-6">
            <blockquote class="text-white max-w-[30ch]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-style:italic;font-size:clamp(18px,2.2vw,24px);line-height:1.35;letter-spacing:-0.02em">
              How might we design adaptive support for women with ADHD that responds to changing cognitive and emotional states?
            </blockquote>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Voices -->
      <div class="mt-16 grid grid-cols-12 gap-8">
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[20px] leading-[1.25] text-white">The voices that changed our direction</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[14px] leading-[1.6] text-white/55 max-w-[32ch]">
            Posts collected from Chinese-language ADHD communities (Dcard, PTT, forums).
            A recurring pattern: suspect, then doubt, then dismiss.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 space-y-5">
          {voices.map((v) => (
            <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-white/35 pl-5 text-white/85" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-style:italic;font-size:clamp(16px,1.8vw,20px);line-height:1.5;letter-spacing:-0.01em">
              {v}
            </blockquote>
          ))}
          <p class="mt-6 text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[60ch]">
            Many women suspect, then doubt, then dismiss. They won't download an app labelled "ADHD" —
            doing so would be admitting something they've been trained to see as a character flaw.
            <strong class="text-white">This was the research moment that changed our brief.</strong>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Six pain points -->
      <div class="mt-16">
        <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 mb-4">The six pain points · each maps to a later design feature</div>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-3">
          {pains.map((p, i) => (
            <article class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">0{i + 1}</div>
              <h4 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[16px] text-white">{p.t}</h4>
              <p class="mt-2 text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/60">{p.d}</p>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- §2 STRATEGY -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 02</span> — The strategic decision
      </div>

      <figure class="my-6 border-l-2 border-white/40 pl-6 md:pl-10">
        <blockquote class="text-white leading-[1.0] max-w-[18ch]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-size:clamp(40px,6.5vw,72px);letter-spacing:-0.03em">
          Optimized for ADHD women.
          <span class="italic block text-white/60">Built for everyone.</span>
        </blockquote>
      </figure>

      <p class="mt-8 text-[15.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[62ch]">
        We chose not to put ADHD in the product name or the front-page copy. The reasoning had two sides.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <article class="rounded-[14px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.04] p-6 md:p-7">
          <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-3">Empathy reason</div>
          <p class="text-[14.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80">
            Many of our target users don't yet know they have ADHD. Labelling the app would activate
            the very self-doubt we were trying to relieve. A woman quietly wondering if she's
            <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">"just bad at life"</em> isn't going to search for "ADHD app."
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="rounded-[14px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.04] p-6 md:p-7">
          <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-3">Strategic reason</div>
          <p class="text-[14.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80">
            A neurotypical-friendly productivity app with ADHD-informed design serves both populations.
            An ADHD-branded app only serves the already-diagnosed.
            <strong class="text-white">Most competitors made the second choice.</strong>
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-8 text-[15.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/60 max-w-[62ch]">
        This is the spine of the whole project. Every feature below exists because we committed to this position.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- §3 THREE DESIGN DECISIONS -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 03</span> — Three decisions that carry the strategy
      </div>

      <!-- 3.1 -->
      <article class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-6 md:gap-8 mb-20">
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
          <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">3.1</div>
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[22px] leading-[1.2] text-white">Gender-inclusive registration</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 space-y-5">
          <figure class="rounded-[16px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden">
            <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6">
              <img
                src={`${base}img/registration.png`}
                alt="Gender-inclusive registration flow — three onboarding screens"
                class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
                loading="lazy"
              />
            </div>
            <div class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-white/[0.04] border-t border-white/10 font-mono text-[9.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/40">
              Fig 3.1 — Onboarding · sex field & optional cycle logging
            </div>
          </figure>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/85 max-w-[62ch]">
            Onboarding asks for sex (woman / man / trans woman / trans man), then optionally logs
            the user's last menstrual cycle before generating a personalised plan.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-[14.5px] leading-[1.6] text-white/70">
            <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span><strong class="text-white">For women with ADHD</strong>, hormone fluctuations measurably affect attention, emotional regulation, and executive function — ignoring this is a common failure mode of generic productivity apps.</span></li>
            <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span><strong class="text-white">For trans users</strong>, a four-option sex field (rather than a binary) signals the product was designed with them in mind, not retrofitted.</span></li>
            <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span><strong class="text-white">The skip button is non-negotiable.</strong> Forcing disclosure before the app has earned trust would break it at the door.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- 3.2 -->
      <article class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-6 md:gap-8 mb-20">
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
          <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">3.2</div>
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[22px] leading-[1.2] text-white">Hormone-aware calendar</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 space-y-5">
          <figure class="rounded-[16px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden">
            <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6">
              <img
                src={`${base}img/calender.png`}
                alt="Hormone-aware calendar showing phase labels alongside tasks"
                class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
                loading="lazy"
              />
            </div>
            <div class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-white/[0.04] border-t border-white/10 font-mono text-[9.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/40">
              Fig 3.2 — Calendar · task colour coding + hormone phase close-up
            </div>
          </figure>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/85 max-w-[62ch]">
            The calendar doesn't just show tasks — it shows hormone phase alongside them. When the user enters
            the luteal phase (often associated with heightened inattention and emotional dysregulation for ADHD
            women), the calendar surfaces a gentle acknowledgment:
          </p>
          <blockquote class="text-white/90 border-l-2 border-white/40 pl-5 max-w-[46ch]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-style:italic;font-size:clamp(20px,2.4vw,26px);line-height:1.4;letter-spacing:-0.01em">
            "You'll likely be more emotional than usual. Be nicer to yourself."
          </blockquote>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/65 max-w-[62ch]">
            What we were trying to avoid: a warning or disability notice.
            What we wanted: something closer to a weather forecast — information that helps you plan,
            without telling you how to feel.
          </p>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 pt-2">
            <div class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">Visibility vs. privacy</div>
              <p class="text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/65">Easy to reach, but not front-and-centre. Someone using the app at work shouldn't have their cycle plastered across the home screen.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">Informative vs. prescriptive</div>
              <p class="text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/65">We only tell users what's likely — never what they should do. The app gives data, and lets them decide.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- 3.3 -->
      <article class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-6 md:gap-8">
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
          <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">3.3</div>
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[22px] leading-[1.2] text-white">Fidget toy + gamified tracking</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 space-y-5">
          <figure class="rounded-[16px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-2">
              <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6">
                <div class="font-mono text-[9px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-black/35 mb-3 flex items-center gap-1.5">
                  <span class="size-1.5 rounded-full bg-black/25 inline-block"></span>
                  Hardware
                </div>
                <img
                  src={`${base}img/fidget_toy.png`}
                  alt="Physical fidget toy — attaches to back of phone via magnetic snap"
                  class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
                  loading="lazy"
                />
              </div>
              <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6 border-l border-black/[0.06]">
                <div class="font-mono text-[9px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-black/60 mb-3 flex items-center gap-1.5">
                  <span class="size-1.5 rounded-full bg-black/55 inline-block"></span>
                  App
                </div>
                <img
                  src={`${base}img/tracking_system.png`}
                  alt="Gamified tracking system — weekly overview and hamster avatar"
                  class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
                  loading="lazy"
                />
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-white/[0.04] border-t border-white/10 font-mono text-[9.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/40">
              Fig 3.3 — Physical fidget toy (NFC snap) · tracking overview & avatar system
            </div>
          </figure>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/85 max-w-[62ch]">
            Fidgeting is a common self-regulation behaviour for ADHD — but most productivity apps treat it as
            a distraction to eliminate. <strong class="text-white">We wanted the opposite: let fidgeting count as engagement.</strong>
          </p>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">The hardware</div>
              <p class="text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/70">A physical fidget toy (designed by our industrial design teammate) attaches to the back of the phone via magnetic snap and mechanical clip. Inside: embedded magnets and NFC zones. Comes in multiple colour profiles, which also unlock as the user levels up.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">The app side</div>
              <p class="text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/70">When the toy detects movement, it feeds the user's virtual hamster avatar. The weekly overview shows fidget cycles per day — making attention habits visible without conscious logging. Achievement milestones, not streaks: hitting a level doesn't punish you for the days you missed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/50 max-w-[62ch]">
            My contribution was on the app side: the weekly overview layout, the collection grid, and how achievement states communicated progress without tipping into pressure.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <!-- §4 OTHER FEATURES -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 04</span> — Other features
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-14">
        <!-- 4.1 Manage Task -->
        <article class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-6 md:gap-8">
          <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
            <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">4.1</div>
            <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[20px] leading-[1.25] text-white">Manage Task — smart breakdown</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-[14px] leading-[1.6] text-white/60">Auto-decomposes complex tasks into steps, lowering the activation energy to start.</p>
            <div class="mt-4 font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-white/40 leading-[1.6]">
              Addresses:<br/>Daily Forgetfulness · Planning Burnout · Time Blindness
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 space-y-5">
            <figure class="rounded-[16px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden">
              <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6">
                <img
                  src={`${base}img/manage_task.png`}
                  alt="Manage Task — task list, focus session, and smart breakdown screens"
                  class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
                  loading="lazy"
                />
              </div>
              <div class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-white/[0.04] border-t border-white/10 font-mono text-[9.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/40">
                Fig 4.1 — Task list · focus session · smart breakdown
              </div>
            </figure>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-[14.5px] leading-[1.6] text-white/80">
              <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span>Today's tasks with colour-coded status (tracking / overdue / complete); each expands into a focus session with the hamster avatar and quick "Take a Break" + "Take a Note" buttons.</span></li>
              <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span><strong class="text-white">Smart Breakdown</strong> — system automatically deconstructs a complex task into smaller steps. Shifts the question from "how do I even begin?" to "which small thing do I do first."</span></li>
              <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span>Progress ring with deadline and time-spent data — so users can see how estimates compare to reality. Over time, builds a more accurate sense of how long things actually take.</span></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- 4.2 Widgets -->
        <article class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-6 md:gap-8">
          <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
            <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-2">4.2</div>
            <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[20px] leading-[1.25] text-white">Customisable widgets</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-[14px] leading-[1.6] text-white/60">Keeps tasks visible outside the app — countering the out-of-sight, out-of-mind failure mode.</p>
            <div class="mt-4 font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-white/40 leading-[1.6]">
              Addresses:<br/>Weak Working Memory · Daily Forgetfulness
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 space-y-5">
            <figure class="rounded-[16px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden">
              <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6">
                <img
                  src={`${base}img/widget.png`}
                  alt="Customisable widgets — fidget tracker, task tracker, calendar on home and lock screen"
                  class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
                  loading="lazy"
                />
              </div>
              <div class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-white/[0.04] border-t border-white/10 font-mono text-[9.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/40">
                Fig 4.2 — Widget types · home screen + lock screen implementation
              </div>
            </figure>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-[14.5px] leading-[1.6] text-white/80">
              <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span><strong class="text-white">Fidget Tracker</strong> — focus ring and running timer; <strong class="text-white">Task Tracker</strong> — today's tasks with status and "Start Tracking" button; <strong class="text-white">Calendar</strong> — month view with due / overdue / finished colour coding.</span></li>
              <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-white/60 font-mono mt-[2px]">→</span><span>Lock screen implementation keeps the plan on the surface of the phone. For a user whose working memory can't hold plans between glances, this is structural, not cosmetic.</span></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- 4.3 Supporting features -->
        <div>
          <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white mb-4">4.3 Supporting features</div>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <article class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <h4 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[16px] text-white">Educational blogs</h4>
              <p class="mt-2 text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/65">Clarify ADHD misconceptions (executive dysfunction, rejection sensitivity) and gently encourage formal diagnosis when patterns resonate. Positioned inside the app so they surface at the right moment.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="rounded-[10px] border border-white/12 bg-white/[0.03] p-5">
              <h4 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[16px] text-white">Cycle Record</h4>
              <p class="mt-2 text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/65">Logs menstrual flow and today's symptoms (inattention spikes, emotional dysregulation, forgetfulness), feeding into the calendar's hormone-phase layer. Users can select common symptoms or add their own.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-[13.5px] leading-[1.55] text-white/50">Each addresses a specific pain point from §01.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- §5 DESIGN ITERATION -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 05</span> — Design iteration
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-white leading-[0.95] max-w-[22ch]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-size:clamp(32px,5vw,56px);letter-spacing:-0.03em">
        V1 leaned pink. <span class="italic text-white/60">V2 leaned purposeful.</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-8 text-[15.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[62ch]">
        An earlier version of the app leaned pink and soft, with a feed-style home screen mixing smart
        reminders, a hormone tracker, a social community, and blog posts. We rebuilt the visual system
        around our three design values: higher-contrast blue and yellow, a focus-forward home screen
        anchored by the hamster avatar and focus timer, and a cleaner task list.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/60 max-w-[62ch]">
        The iteration sharpened what the app was <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">for</em> — less wellness-feed, more daily companion.
      </p>
      <figure class="mt-10 rounded-[16px] border border-white/12 overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-white p-4 md:p-6">
          <img
            src={`${base}img/iteration.png`}
            alt="Design iteration — V1 pink feed-style vs V2 focus-forward layout"
            class="w-full h-auto rounded-[8px] shadow-[0_2px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.10)]"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-white/[0.04] border-t border-white/10 font-mono text-[9.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/40">
          Fig 5 — Design iteration · V1 (feed-style) vs. V2 (focus-forward)
        </div>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- §6 USER TESTING -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 06</span> — User testing
      </div>
      <p class="text-[15.5px] leading-[1.65] text-white/80 max-w-[62ch]">
        Qualitative testing with participants who self-identify as having ADHD.
        A full SUS-style quantitative comparison wasn't in scope — what we were testing was whether the
        product's <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">core premise</em> resonated.
      </p>
      <figure class="mt-10 border-l-2 border-white/40 pl-6 md:pl-10">
        <blockquote class="text-white/90 max-w-[30ch]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-style:italic;font-size:clamp(22px,3.2vw,34px);line-height:1.3;letter-spacing:-0.02em">
          "As someone with ADHD, I think this design is incredibly ADHD-friendly. The toy and hormone function differentiate the app from other productivity apps."
        </blockquote>
      </figure>
      <p class="mt-6 text-[14.5px] leading-[1.6] text-white/60 max-w-[60ch]">
        The second sentence is what mattered to us most. The differentiation we'd been arguing about in team
        meetings for weeks had actually landed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- §7 VALUES -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 07</span> — Design values
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        {values.map((v, i) => (
          <article>
            <div class="text-white leading-none text-[52px]" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;letter-spacing:-0.03em">0{i + 1}</div>
            <h3 class="mt-3 font-sans font-semibold text-[18px] text-white">{v.t}</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-[14px] leading-[1.6] text-white/65">{v.d}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- §8 REFLECTION -->
    <section class="mt-24 md:mt-32">
      <div class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-white/50 border-t border-white/15 pt-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-white">§ 08</span> — Reflection
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-10 max-w-[64ch]">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[19px] text-white mb-2">What the project taught me.</h3>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/75">
            The most valuable moment of the project wasn't a design decision — it was the research finding
            that forced us to rewrite our brief. We'd started assuming we were building
            <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">"an ADHD app for women."</em> We ended up building
            <em class="italic text-white" style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif">"a productivity app that happens to be ADHD-informed"</em> —
            because we'd learned that the first framing would have excluded the users we most wanted to reach.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-4 text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/85">
            Research isn't a box to check before design starts. It can — and should — reshape the fundamental
            premise of what you're making.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[19px] text-white mb-2">What I'd do differently.</h3>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/75">
            We didn't run a head-to-head test against a competitor (Todoist, Tiimo) to validate that our
            specific design choices made the ADHD-women use case measurably easier. Without it, the honest
            version of our claim is "our target users found it differentiated," not "they found it more effective."
            <strong class="text-white">Good case studies say both.</strong>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-sans font-semibold text-[19px] text-white mb-2">What I'll bring forward.</h3>
          <p class="text-[15px] leading-[1.65] text-white/75">
            Inclusive design decisions (like the four-option sex field) are cheap to make at design time and
            costly to retrofit later. This project pushed me to make them at the start, not as a later
            accessibility pass.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

